p;margin:0\"><img role=\"presentation\" class=\"imageDropZone mceImage\" src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/1ba58762-dc8e-eb94-8b95-d023bc4cf9d3.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"520.1999999999999\" height=\"auto\" style=\"display:block;max-width:520.1999999999999px;width:520.1999999999999px;height:auto\"/></span>\n<![endif]-->\n</td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-723\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b723\"><table id=\"section_0db4779e7618e2b5a5a2e5196db225c9\"><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--39\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b-22\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--50\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b722\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId-721\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-580\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b580\"><table><tbody><tr><td><span>New wines in the door!</span><p><strong><span>Oenops Apla Rose:</span></strong><span><span><span><span>A delightfully complex Rose from Greece that's both round and crisp. Strawberry and raspberry plus a fun kiss of peach fuzz lead the way. A bit of lees-aging lends texture while citrus fruit acidity keeps the palate fresh. A great pairing for all manner of pastas and salads.</span></span></span></span></p><p><strong><span><span><span><span>Azienda Agricola Luigi Giordano Vino Rosso</span></span></span></span></strong><span><span><span><span>: A gorgeous new red from the Barbaresco appellation of Piedmont - check out Julie’s writeup, below, for all the details!</span></span></span></span></p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b724\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b416\"><!--[if !mso]><!--><table><tbody><tr><td><img src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/9a1c764d-c0e5-5a5f-9ad3-d30cf17d8422.jpeg\" width=\"520\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></td></tr></tbody></table><!--<![endif]-->\n<!--[if mso]>\n<span class=\"mceImageBorder\" style=\"border:0;border-width:2px;vertical-align:top;margin:0\"><img role=\"presentation\" class=\"imageDropZone mceImage\" src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/9a1c764d-c0e5-5a5f-9ad3-d30cf17d8422.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"520.1999999999999\" height=\"auto\" style=\"display:block;max-width:520.1999999999999px;width:520.1999999999999px;height:auto\"/></span>\n<![endif]-->\n</td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-415\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b415\"><table><tbody><tr><td>Wine we’re drinking this week:<p><span><span><span>For anyone who's seen me in the shop recently, you may have noticed the bumps, scrapes, bruises, and bug bites that currently litter my arms. I've spent some portion of the last couple of weekends helping friends destroy their old, rundown shed / greenhouse-add-on so they can build a shiny new structure in its place. (The before and after photos are going to be great.) This work has been a mix of creative use of various tools, blind determination, and brute force, and it has been oh so sweaty. Each time I have finished this work I've been sweaty and tired but have also carried a feeling of accomplishment and satisfaction at a hard day's work. Now normally you'd think this situation would call for a shower beer, but what I most wanted was food. All the food. And what goes better with food than wine?</span></span></span></p><p><span><span><span>Now you guys know me and you know I'll rock a sparkler or a white but my heart belongs to red. So what to do when it's hot as hell, you've just finished sweaty work, and you still want red? Enter the chillable red. The latest chillable red to grace our shelves is the </span></span></span><strong><span><span><span>Azienda Agricola Luigi Giordano Vino Rosso </span></span></span></strong><span><span><span>from Piedmont. The Giordano family vineyards go back several generations but it wasn't until the 1950s that Luigi started vinifying their grapes, rather than selling them all. Today Luigi's daughter and grandson run the vineyard and cellar. The Vino Rosso is 85% Nebbiolo but this is not your father's Nebbiolo. Here it's paired with 15% Arneis to help soften the acidity and tannins Nebbiolo is known for. The result is a fantastically aromatic red that's light on its feet, with lots of juicy red fruit and berries. There's a lovely earthiness and a touch of grip to help remind you this is indeed Italian red, but it stays fresh throughout. This bottle is a great pairer with pasta (with red sauce!), salads, or poultry. You don't have to chill this red down, but it's really great if you do. And if you've been wielding a sledge hammer and a crowbar all day, then I definitely recommend the chill.</span></span></span></p><p>.</p><p><em><span><span><span><span>This week’s writeup is brought to you by Julie.</span></span></span></span></em></p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b508\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-452\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b452\"><table id=\"section_b111a6056d437a4488ce3582ec83de93\"><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--33\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b-10\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--44\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b456\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId-455\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b453\"><!--[if !mso]><!--><table><tbody><tr><td><img src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/8dc66e9b-7305-c0d1-5572-f12ee7415bed.jpeg\" width=\"534\" loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\"></td></tr></tbody></table><!--<![endif]-->\n<!--[if mso]>\n<span class=\"mceImageBorder\" style=\"border:0;border-width:2px;vertical-align:top;margin:0\"><img role=\"presentation\" class=\"imageDropZone mceImage\" src=\"https://mcusercontent.com/be20bbfba341582993786f7f0/images/8dc66e9b-7305-c0d1-5572-f12ee7415bed.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"533.8\" height=\"auto\" style=\"display:block;max-width:533.8px;width:533.8px;height:auto\"/></span>\n<![endif]-->\n</td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-454\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b454\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p><span><span>July Tasting Events coming your way!</span></span></p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b457\"><table><tbody><tr><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"gutterContainerId-177\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b177\"><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Thanks for your business! See you soon, Beth, Julie &amp; Aidan and the entire Brew Crew</p></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table><!--[if (gte mso 9)|(IE)]></td></tr></table><![endif]--></td></tr></tbody><tbody><tr><td><!--[if (gte mso 9)|(IE)]><table align=\"center\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\" width=\"660\" style=\"width:660px;\"><tr><td><![endif]--><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--31\"><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"b9\"><table><tbody><tr><td><table><tbody><tr><td id=\"mceColumnId--6\"><table><tbody><tr></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr><tr><td id=\"b15\"></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table></td></tr></tbody></table><!--[if (gte mso 9)|(IE)]></td></tr></table